<meta name="socialpost1" content="Early last year, Gov. Ron DeSantis began signing death warrants at a faster rate than ever before. What followed was the most intense period of executions the state has carried out in more than eight decades." />
<meta name="socialpost2" content="As most states move away from the death penalty, Florida is executing more prisoners than ever before. Last year, 19 people were put to death — shattering the state’s previous annual record of 11, first set in 1936." />
<meta name="socialpost3" content="Trump has made the death penalty a cornerstone of his law-and-order agenda. Nowhere has his vision been pursued more relentlessly than in Florida, thanks to an unusual concentration of power in the governor’s office." />
<meta name="socialpost4" content="In Florida, the governor has full authority on whether — and when — to sign a death warrant. And that decision is made behind closed doors, so there’s no way to know what criteria is used when choosing who will be put to death." />
<meta name="socialpost5" content="Secrecy surrounding executions in Florida has left victims’ families, prisoners and lawyers searching for clues about the governor’s selection process. “He could be deciding who is next to die by throwing darts at a list of names,” one lawyer said." />
